commentBody:
@Anonymous i’m back to the beginning of the lockdown in the archives: March 2020. I only do Thursday, Friday and Saturday.

Even with an open mind, I don’t understand how you can equate this puzzle to a Wednesday puzzle of old. I’m not disputing your experience. I’m just saying I can’t really relate.

Thank you for the reply.

@Steven M.

I don’t think it’s fair to say that the “S” in time zones such as PST is strictly there to distinguish between DST and non-DST.

In fact, the notion of “standard” time zones appears to have predated DST by a few decades: <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_time_in_the_United_States" target="_blank">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_time_in_the_United_States</a>

@Steven M.

This is kind of a prickly one! It’s pretty clear that the standardized Pacific time zone was created in 1883, and it’s equally clear that nowadays, the “S” in PST largely serves to distinguish that from PDT.

But what I can’t immediately find is when the term “Pacific Standard Time” was coined. I’m *betting* the answer is 1883…but in 5+ minutes of searching, I haven’t been able to answer that definitively.

@Marshall Walthew

"I especially liked “comment for one who’s going along” for WHENINROME,"

ET TU, amigo! Ain't it just the way - you're stumped and staring at all those unfilled spaces, but the with of a well-turned clue keeps you in the game . . .then you keep at it and we'll,  all roads lead to . . .

@SP

Ditto!
You've captured the thrill of solving this gem of a crossword puzzle quite well. Like you, looking forward to another one.

@Edward I agree with the HTTP complaint, too vague a clue.

Also, "a ding thing" is an awful clue - why would someone necessarily equate a "ding", which is a very specific sound, to a text message? Any sound can be used for a text message notification, and a ding could be used for any infinite number of things. How many people actually have that as their notification sound for a text? A good clue / answer pair should have at least one of the two parts be very specific and unique. This one had neither.

I don't mind hard, but this puzzle seemed overly complicated, even for a Friday. I was almost double my average Friday time.

@Edward

Funny, I struggled with some of the entries you highlighted…but came away with exactly the opposite overall impression.

As SP said, this is *exactly* the kind of puzzle lots of us hope for on Fridays (though TBH, still decidedly on the easy side for a Friday, let alone Saturday, by historical standards).

@Katie,

That shocked me, too. In a bad way. 

I for one was grateful to have a Friday puzzle that took me more than one sitting to get through. It’s been too long since I’ve had an experience like that.

@Rodzu

Did you, like moi, have that "DOH!" moment when the HTTP penny dropped?

I thought it was especially fiendish of Rafael and Geoffrey to sidle that up against the AHAS of tortured discovery - it was only a TEXT away ...

@Jim

I think it's intentional.  People who can call up words easily, as I assume constructors and cluers can, could certainly monkey around with a clue to get two or three "reasonable" answers.

It's also quite impressive.

@Isabeau

I should have added...

"The only one I got without any crosses was SEXMANUALS."

@Isabeau
I'm a tech girl too but I had to scratch for every blessed letter in the NW bloc. Between HTTP(s) where I started with sTeP(s) and TEXT where, like most of us, I started with 'bell', I felt like a mountain climber with nothing to hold on to.
Whoof!

@Weak

Fortunately, it doesn't seem to have been "too easy".  

But I am always uneasy about the "too easy" because my heinie's been right well kicked.

@Mike
If a princess wears one, is it a Divestment?
Asking for a friend.

@Matt
I dig the staccato of vague…mist…murk. 

Puzzles (and life) become their most beguiling selves in hazy…mazy…grey.

@Becky

Word.

Art, especially.

@Francis

Traumatized fist bump?

🤜🏾🤛🏾

@Andrzej

It's good to hear your praise for a puzzle.  I have to admit, to you and to myself, I look to you, as I do others here, for self-confirmation of my opinion of a puzzle.  

I thought this was a quality puzzle, and at the half-way mark I'd probably have given myself a one-in-six chance of solving it cleanly.

@Francis

I don't recommend looking to me for anything, maybe except for picking a color for your car (no, matte or sheen-less grey is *not* a good choice, are you ins@ne?)

I also thought I would most likely not be able to finish the puzzle, but it felt so well constructed I gladly persevered, and it paid off.

@Andrzej
On avoiding nativity crossings… 
“don’t crash the crèche, we’ll crush him later…”

@Andrzej
Glad to see that you have observed the Net's oldest rule: every post correcting an error must itself contain an error.
Bravo!

@Andrzej - I think the original TED talks are often worthwhile But the franchise -- the TEDx talks, are all over the place. 

But there are occasional gems, such as this one -- the best part of which is excerpted in this video. (I am ignoring the fact that he can't pronounce "interstitial" correctly...) 

<a href="https://youtu.be/2FMBSblpcrc?si=9EgqCS9kVzSSyWn4" target="_blank">https://youtu.be/2FMBSblpcrc?si=9EgqCS9kVzSSyWn4</a>

@Mark Smith
You must have listened to different ones than I've heard.  I admit I've only heard a few (suggested by friends, usually) but those few were wonderful.  

Being a harsh critic myself, I can believe that you and Andrzej must just not have come across the better TALKs.

@EnglishRose
I also had never heard MANIOC. It has always been cassava or yuca where I went. Apparently, a manifestation of my limited experience. 

I had heard of EARLAP before, but never understood why it wasn’t flap.

@Cat Lady Margaret 

"Totes yum" will never pass my lips.

Well, maybe once, just to watch my sons' reaction.

@Vaer
I thought of the Rolling Stones first. Their first album from their new home was fittingly called, "Exile on Main St."

@Jane
That subject is quite the hot topic in NYC at the moment, thanks to their new ultra-left mayor. They're all fleeing to Texas and Florida, at least for the better part of the year.

@Hitch

Could it be possible that you’re just not there yet?

I thought it was a very good puzzle for a Friday because it made me think, and there was nothing that I found problematic. Those who found things to be problematic just didn’t know them or understand them.

@NanuNanu Me too! I searched for “Nash”
just to see if anyone else had made the same mistake. I really thought that was his name!

I didn’t even catch it until the end. There’s a kit for that? omg. fantastic.

@Steve L
Yes, I wasn't quibbling about the clue, but validating Kate's response as a logical one.

I first thought of the theatre, then the city.

@MOL
My grandmother used to say, "We're going to have some kind of falling weather." 

That covered it all.

@Vaer

Ditto for bell on [Ding thing]. When I finally *finally* took it out... I still didn't get it, going for pilESON instead of the more hateful version. Once I took *that* out, the corner filled so swiftly! 

That EARLAP tho... I think my biggest hangup there was not seeing SLIPS for [Flubs]. A flub is certainly more significant than a slip (IMHO!).

@The X-Phile

OP does not need to justify his feelings/experience to you or this chat. There are PLENTY of comments here where the opinions are not (ahem) 'justified'...(let alone 'justified' to YOU)...but you haven't audited those...so, again, feels like you're just picking on someone who disagrees with you. 

'Possibility of a discussion' (let alone a discussion with you) is not the objective of commenting.

@SP
'Self-centered' nailed it.
Give a reason, else who cares?

@Ben Blackwell

“This is a terrible puzzle.”

“Jacob deGrom is a terrible pitcher. I can’t even manage a foul ball off of him.”

@Anonymous
Thanks for mentioning MANIOC, which I got on crossings despite its lumpiness. When you say it 'does not look like a real word to me,' I understand completely. 
Every word has its own "shape", some of which reflect sources far distant from English. It's why you pause when crossings give you BN or YJ as consecutive letters. (Don't worry, you're OK. You're on your way to GLIBNESS or PYJAMAS.) There's something in your head, derived from your accumulated experience of English,  that says  'That's not a word.'

@Barry Ancona

Nice to see a really hard Friday for a change.  I did beat that median solve time, but still quite a bit slower than my own Friday average.

And of course, there are some who think that because of that, it's a horrible puzzle.

@Sue
It did indeed work well. Some collaborative efforts feel like two puzzles jammed together, despite the best efforts of the editors.

My cell phone chimes when I get a TEXT.

@Rick 

"But if it's a fox, I'll make a fine hood of it, with long earlaps."
— The Owl's Ear by Émile Erckmann and Alexandre Chatrian

@Nora
Haha- my first try was "SKI hill",
Thanks to growing up in not-mountainous Wisconsin .

@Mean Old Lady
Some medical schools have an actual "white coat" ceremony where the first- years are formally issued them. On the other side, many doctors, especially pediatricians, are aware of the problem you mention and either don't wear coats or wear less scary patterned ones and/or tone them down with goofy attachments. 
  And it's not just kids.  "White coat syndrome" refers to any patient whose blood pressure is higher in the doctor's office than at home.

@RozzieGrandma
I am well aware of all that, but it wasn't pertinent to our experience.  
Our daughter still attracts groups of Med students due to some of her diagnoses.  She told me about one group of students who were asked to speculate about her elevated BP.  Theycsme up with all sorts of guesses.  Then the preceptor asked them, "How about being unclothed in front of a group of strangers and discussed like an inanimate object?"

@nd
There has been no shortage of fakes this week. News, Amazon products, and now answers.
(Did I pluralize “fake” correctly?)😋

@Charlotte K
Same. Difficult. NW. Break. Finished. WAY above average time.
I liked it.

@Shari Coats

Have you tried opening the puzzle on your Mac multiple times?

I’ve noticed that when I solve a puzzle on one device, then open it on another, the grid is sometimes empty on the second device — but only the first time I load it.

@Gareth Baird
It is a thing.
You're on the internet...you could look it up.

@HeathieJ
That is so painful. Any family gathering in Georgia--same.

I learned to start saying 30 minutes before I wanted to leave. You have to introduce the idea gently.
